deck_excerpt: Semi-competitive Zombie Deck based around Endless Decay and Zombie World. Negation-heavy, graveyard heavy.
deck_description: As the title suggests, this deck revolves around Endless Decay as the boss monster, and utilizes the effects of Zombie World to access the GYs (as well as slow your opponent down). Zombie World will prevent some opponents from running their decks properly, as it changes all monsters in the GYs and on the field to Zombie type. Endless Decay is works best when it is summoned early, as it's ATK is whatever your opponent's LP are, divided by 2, at the time of summon. It is especially potent in 2v2, where if summoned first turn, it has 8000 ATK. Watch out for Solemn Judgement, as a well-timed use will almost completely negate the firepower of this deck.  There are quite a few negate cards that will give you some breathing room to summon ED and the other powerful powerful monsters. Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend is especially potent and relatively simple to special summon (so long as you can keep alive at least one of its synchro materials. Always try to have Zombie World on the field. It will make a handful of summons very easy as well as mess up your opponent when they need to tribute. Red-eyes Zombie Dragon becomes more powerful with each Zombie monster on the field and in the GYs, so it can be a very reliable late-game Synchro monster it's too late to summon an Endless Decay or too difficult to summon Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend.     A few tips:  Special summon Endless Decay as early as possible. Use Pyramid Turtle to bait opponent into attacking for a special summon from the deck of a 2000 or less DEF Zombie Monster (Endless Decay, Doomking Balerdroch). Use Mezukis and then Burial From a Different Dimension to ensure that the useful effect monsters can continue to be summoned from the graveyard. Fusion Summon Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon with SuperPoly after placing Zombie World in a field zone.  Use Tatsunecro, Glow-Up Bloom, and Jack-O-Bolan to Syncro-Summon Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend (when Zombie World is on the field), and wipe the field during MP1.  Negate opponent's Summons with Enma's Judgement, Doomking (during a chain) and Ash Blossom.  Use Foolish Burial to put an Endless Decay in the GY as soon as possible, then Mezuki, Monster Reborn, Book of Life, or Jack-O-Bolan to Special Summon.  Banish Necroworld Banshee to put Zombie World on the field, then use Burial From a Different Dimension to put NB back in the GY, then Special Summon it onto the field to protect Zombie World.        Note: This is my first post to ygoprodeck but I have been utilizing this deck (and older variations of it) for almost 2 years and I believe it is now fun and effective enough to share with the world.

deck_excerpt: An update to my original "Charming Magicians" Deck, which seems to have gotten fairly popular. This Deck strategy is more or less the same. However, t
deck_description:
*[EDIT: Check "Ideal Starting Hand" Section] An update to my original "Charming Magicians" Deck, which seems to have gotten fairly popular. This Deck strategy is more or less the same. However, there are now 50 cards, and I got rid of some of the fluff, removing many monsters that didn't work in tandem with the "Possessed" Spell/Traps (Ichirin [F], Awakening [∞], & Teamwork, Unpossessed [∞]), and actually replacing them with monsters that have more combo potential with this Deck in general. Changes: The Deck's goal is still to try and get out ⌈Fortune Lady Every⌋, and then ⌈Datascape Fox - XianXian⌋. I ended up removing ⌈Explosive Magician⌋, because while its effect is useful, unlike ⌈Arcanite Magician⌋, it doesn't give itself Spell Counters upon summoning, making its effect useless if it's the only monster on the field. Plus, ⌈Arcanite Magician⌋ is just better anyway, since you aren't limited to just Spell/Traps. I also removed ⌊Leviar the Sea Dragon⌋ and swapped it for ⌈Time Thief Redoer⌋. I actually haven't tested this change out yet, and I may even end up switching it up again, but I found myself NEVER using ⌊Leviar the Sea Dragon⌋, even when it may have worked. I also wanted to put in an Xyz monster that required less monsters to Special Summon, since both of the Spellcaster Xyz monsters require 3 Level 4 monsters, which can be difficult for a single turn. I ended up side-decking DNA Surgery [∞] and Chocolate Magician Girl. I also ended up removing Wynn the Wind Medium/Channeler, Magical Exemplar, Spiritual Earth Art - Kurogane, and Dark Spirit Art - Greed. Wynn was occasionally useful, but any time I had the choice to Special Summon or add a Charmer to my hand, I would just end up going for the "Familiar Possessed" monsters. They are objectively more useful in this deck for 2 reasons. For one, they are Level 4, so they are not only easier to summon, but are much more useful for Xyz and Synchro Summoning. Second, there aren't too many WIND monsters in this Deck, so using Wynn's effect to Summon it isn't readily useful, unless you have multiple Wynn the Wind Charmer monsters in your deck. Magical Exemplar is in a similar boat, because it can be situationally useful, but its ATK/DEF don't mesh with the deck well. I got rid of Spritual Earth Art because Nefarious Archfiend of Nefariousness has basically the same effect, but it Destroys the monster instead of Tributing it, so it can activate Unpossessed's [∞] effect with little cost. I got rid of Greed because it is SUPER risky to use since most decks run on Spells, whereas Traps are much rarer. Finally, I added Fairy Tail - Luna, Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Dogmatika Theo, the Iron Punch, Archnemeses Protos, and one more Awakening of the Possessed [∞]. Ideal Starting Hand: (2nd turn) *[Edit: I misread Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous's effect. Once you use its effect to add Monster to your hand, you cannot Extra Deck-summon. Also, I overlooked Angraecum Umbrella's effect, which limits you to Synchro Summoning after you use its effect.]
  • Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin [F], (Either of these Familiar Possessed monsters: Eria or Wynn), Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Nefarious Archfiend of Nefariousness, Angraecum Umbrella
This hand is perfect if you go second. Especially if your opponent already has Extra Deck monsters on the field (This hand also assumes your opponent has an Extra Deck monster out). Even more perfect if your opponent has mostly EARTH monsters.
  1. First Activate Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin [∞]. Doing this first can (1) bait your opponent's first negate, so that your next few moves can avoid being negated, and (2) prevent 1 negate once you do the next move.
  2. Special Summon Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous with its effect.
  3. Next, Special Summon Nefarious Archfiend of Nefariousness.
  4. Then Special Summon Awakening of the Possessed - Archfiend Reaper of Nefariousness from the Deck using Nefarious and Ecclesia. Then bring back Ecclesia from the GY with Awakening - Archfiend's effect (this way you still have a 1500 DEF Spellcaster, in case your opponent uses a monster effect).
  5. Now Link Summon ⌈Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovible⌋ with Awakening - Archfiend and whichever monster you brought back with Awakening - Archfiend's effect. Then bring out: (route A) Unpossessed [∞] with Awakening - Archfiend's other effect (only if your opponent has NO EARTH monsters in the GY). (route B) Awakening of the Possessed [∞] with Awakening - Archfiend's other effect (only if your opponent has EARTH monsters in the GY).
 
  • (6A) Then set Unpossessed [∞].
  1. (7A) Now that there is a monster in your GY, Normal Summon Angraecum Umbrella, using its effect to discard your Familiar Possessed monster and Special Summon either Lv 4 Spellcaster monster from your GY. (Remember from now on, you can only Summon Synchros from the Extra Deck)
  2. (8A) Then Synchro Summon ⌈Fortune Lady Every⌋ with your Lv 4 Spellcaster monster and Angraecum Umbrella.
  3. (9A) Then on the next turn, activate Unpossessed [∞] before your opponent destroys either monster.
 
  • (6B) Then activate Awakening of the Possessed [∞].
  1. (7B) Use ⌈Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovible's⌋ effect to Special Summon one of your opponent's GY EARTH monsters.
  2. (8B) Use that Special Summoned monster and ⌈Aussa⌋ to Link Summon ⌈Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians⌋ (Only do this if there are enough Spells on the Field and in both GYs to use its effect), then you get your Draw from Awakening of the Possessed's [∞] effect.
  3. (9B) Then use ⌈Selene's⌋ effect to Special Summon Ecclesia.
  4. (10B) Use Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin's[∞] effect to swap out your Familiar Possessed monster for the respective "Familiar" monster (Jigabyte, Ranryu). Special Summon that monster you added to your hand with its effect.
  5. (11B) Special Summon either Awakening - Gogigabyte or Awakening - Rasenryu using the respective Familiar monster and ⌈Selene⌋, then use its Special Summon effect for your benefit.
  6. (12B) Normal Summon Angraecum Umbrella. Depending on the card you drew with Awakening of the Possessed's [∞] effect, at your own discretion, you can try using the monster's effect to resurrect a GY monster (Remember from now on, you can only Summon Synchros from the Extra Deck).
  7. (13B) Then Synchro Summon ⌈Fortune Lady Every⌋ with your Lv 4 Spellcaster (presumably Ecclesia) and Angraecum Umbrella.
If all goes well, both routes would start you off with ⌈Fortune Lady Every⌋ and another powerful monster, as well as card effect or battle protection with your Continuous Spell/Trap. They also both set you up next turn for more combos. For other useful strategies in this deck, check out my other Charmer Deck, because many of those strategies apply here.

deck_excerpt: Control oriented Shaddoll Dogmatika deck
deck_description:
Pure Shaddoll with a very small Dogmatika engine splashed to search for Schism by dumping Apkallone. No fixed combo as this is mainly a control deck with Ariel, Dinomischus, Fleurdelis and Winda. There are 3 main ways to get Schism:
  1. Nadir, dump Apkallone, search Schism and dump another Shaddoll with Apkallone's effect
  2. Fuse 2 Shaddolls into Apkallone in EMZ, make Gravity Controller.
  3. Fuse 1 Shaddoll and 1 Light into Construct in EMZ, dump Schism, make Gravity Controller.
Most hands just try to end on Winda, with possibly an additional Ecclesia, which may not seem that threatening, but remember that our board is often protected by a big handtrap count, as well as powerful Traps like Punishment, and Dinomiscus which offer a lot of advantage. There is a 50-card variant that is more Trap-heavy, which is stronger if you can't make Winda, but at the tradeoff of being able to make Winda less consistently. + 2 Ecclesia, +1 Fleurdelis, +1 Maximus, +1 Punishment +2 Torrential Tribute, + 3 Trap Trick +1 Titaniklad in Extra Deck by replacing whatever

deck_description: Your board should look something like Buster Dragon and Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman equipped with Dragon Buster Destruction Sword, Wizard Buster Destruction Sword, or Robot Buster Destruction Sword depending on opponent's deck (most likely Dragon Buster). This deck is Synchro-focused but you can easily make a link focused version. An example of a 1 turn combo: -Special summon 1 of either Fiend's Sanctuary, Jester Confit or Tenyi Spirit - Adhara -Use Where Arf Thou? to add Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman or Dragon Buster Destruction Sword to hand(whichever you don't have, Buster Whelp being more important) -Normal summon Buster Whelp and add Buster Blader, the Destruction Swordmaster to hand -Link summon Protector Whelp of the Destruction Swordmaster to SS Buster Blader from hand and send Destruction Sword Memories to GY -SS Buster Whelp from GY and/or equip Dragon Buster from hand to Buster Blader and then SS it -Link summon Linkross to summon two tokens and then summon Crystron Halqifibrax -Synchro summon Buster Dragon and use it's effect to SS Buster Blader from GY if you can use it as material again otherwise leave it in GY -Use Destruction Sword Memories in GY to fusion summon Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman -During opponent's turn, use Buster Dragon's effect to equip an approproiate monster to Buster Blader from GY -During opponent's turn, use Halqifibrax to summon Shooting Riser Dragon and optionally send an equippable monster to GY. It can then be used with the tokens to summon another synchro -Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman alone can be enough to get the combo mentioned in the first paragraph again if you get wiped

deck_excerpt: Solid and consistent
deck_description: This is a pretty standard invoked dogmatika build but with a little shaddoll thrown in and the dragoon package. I play three Fleur De Les because you can sometimes set him up on your opponents turn and then if you have another or draw into another you have a negate set up. Also, this card helps to bring out dragoon as when its effects activate it does NOT lock you out of your extra deck. You then could easily go into aliester and if you have a light in your hand or opponents gy you can link Aliester into Almirja and then fuse into mechaba anf then link Almirja and Fleur De Les into Predaplant. You would finish the turn with a mechaba and a dragoon possibly. Another great set up is getting winda and Dragoon or Mechaba on the field at the same time. This really makes it tough for your opponent to play if they do not have dark ruler or droplet. Foolish burial is huge for when you need to set up some Shadoll stuff or send aliester to the gy if you draw into invocation without him. I also really like siding in the Invoker of Maddness because his name changes to Aleister in the gy, so you can set your gy for next turn with nadir. Finally, I just wanted to shoud out ice dragon's prison. This card has been unbelievable for me so far. I think it is highly under rated and should be considered more for the called by the grave replacement people are looking for. Still need help with the extra deck so any suggestions would be welcome!

deck_excerpt: An actual Invoked Dogmatika engine that uses the Shaddoll engine in that main deck thats not just Schism.
deck_description: An Invoked Dogmatika that uses the Shaddoll engine in the main deck for more faster, and aggressive turns.  Use Nadir Servant to set up by tossing Apkallone into the GY to search for any Shaddoll card THEN discard a shaddoll monster to proc their effect. The deck runs less hand traps (8) compared to the usual Invoked Dogmatika deck (12-15) but it can easily set up more aggressive pushes and a more consistent Winda.  Reason I use Veiler over Imperm because I would be able to use Veiler as fusion fodder for more consistent Mechaba/Construct (better this format because CBTG is at 1) but imperm works as well.  I do really like Schism because this build thins the deck out so well and you are able to get out easy Winda/Construct/Apkallone plays on opponent turns and act as a disruptor to remove 1 monster in the field (doesn't target or destroy).  -You can use Apkallone to negate monster effects/Winda as floodgate/Construct plays to dump cards like Ariel and Dragon which is really useful against banishing Eldlich from the GY and destroying Field Spells (Boot, Numeron Network, Ravine, etc) in this meta.  Alternative Builds:  -You can remove the Resh/Cross-Sheep for 1 more hand trap and replace Cross-sheep for a 5k ATK fusion monster (Five-Headed Dragon or Dragon Master Knight) for a higher ceiling atk removal for Dogmatika Punishment or Augoeides 8k ATK OTK. However, going against towers/Dragoon requires link 4s like Borrelsword or Accesscode to get over ATK threshold which resh/cross-sheep can help pump out.  -You can actually add more hand-traps and the deck can still run smoothly at 42-43.  -Add Predaplant in Extra but I did not really use the card often so I opted with a Cross-Sheep instead as an extender. If you still want cross-sheep with Predaplant, you can take out 1 Mechaba/Winda/Construct.  -Foolish burial is a great searcher (dump Hedgehog/Ariel) or a way to reduce opponent's resources in GY and S/T zone (Ariel/Dragon).  Overall, I am very happy with this build but if there is something I can improve, please let me know in the comments or your thoughts :)

deck_excerpt: A good budget option and a good beginner option for those looking to play at competitive events.

The easiest way to do this is to use on of the tenyi spirit monster in your main deck to special summon it as long as you dont control a effect monster, the use that special summoned monster to link summon into monk of the tenyi which is a non-effect monster allowing you to keep special summoning and linking off into others without using your normal summon.

deck_excerpt: Domain Monarch build for September 2020
deck_description: THE MONARCH'S RISE! With Pantheism of the Monarch's moving from Limited to Unlimited in the recent Limited & Forbidden List, it's time to revisit an old classic. This build of Monarch's focuses on the Field Spell "Domain of the True Monarchs" which restricts your opponent from Summoning Extra Deck monsters while boosting the ATK/DEF of your Tribute Summoned monsters as well as reducing the Levels of your higher-level Monarchs, allowing for you to Tribute Summon them using only one Monster. The main board you want to make if going first is Vanity's Fiend, Domain, and The Monarch's Erupt set. This stops your opponent from Special Summoning while protecting Vanity's from monster effects due to Erupt as well from battle due to Domain (Vanity's Fiend will gain 800 ATK from Domain, giving it 3200 ATK during combat only.) Erebus and Ehther are both at 3 in this deck due to their strong on-field effects and utility. Some small tech cards include Thestalos the Mega Monarch to give us information about the opponent's hand as well as disrupting their plays, Called by the Grave to prevent Edea from being Ashed, Foolish Burial to dump Erebus, Upstart Goblin for extra consistency, and one Kuraz for consistency as well as getting rid of The Prime Monarch. Any suggestions for improvement are welcome in the comments. :)

deck_excerpt: Fossil Fusion and Invocation
deck_description: Fossils and Invoked engine, what can go wrong? I've tried a lot of hybrid strategies with Fossils and I think this is the strongest one so far. The Invoked engine has decent synergy with the Fossil engine, as well as covering a good amount of Fossils' weaknesses. Fossils are at their worst going 1st, whereas Invoked has gives you access to reasonable lines going 1st while not asking for too much deck space or many specific cards in hand. This is the biggest draw to this particular hybrid. I've also enjoyed using Fossils with other fusion archetypes because Weathering Soldier has good synergy with effects that send him to the GY, including fusion spells. If given the choice we will go 2nd. Main deck: Nibiru - A big rock monster for Fossil Fusion, as well as a light to get access to Mechaba. He also has the benefit of setting up our opponent's GY for our Fossil Fusion and Invocation. Kumongous - Kaiju's as a great way to both take care of annoying cards on our opponent's board as well as set up their GY for a Skullgios fusion. Kumongous gets the nod over Gameciel due to his Earth type. Extra deck space is limited in this deck and there is not room for the Water Invoked fusion. We're good at dumping attack onto the board, so the extra 200 attack from Kumongous won't be a problem. Weathering Soldier - Our tutor for the Fossil archetype. Works when being fused with Invocation from the hand, as well as with Foolish Burial, Miracle Rupture, and Mathematician. He also beats down quite wel. Staple for all Fossil strats. Aleister the Invoker - We're playing Invoked, so obviously we play him. Note he can choose any fusion monster, not just Invoked ones. This can lead to huge damage with Skullking, or even with a Skullgios if you played it off of Time Stream. Mathematician - Aleister is obviously our #1 normal summon most of the time, but we won't always have him. Mathematician bulks up our count to help ensure we have a strong enabler to normal summon. Dumping Weathering Soldier or Keystone can be great, and he's also a 1500 attack monster to res off of Cross-Sheep. Ash Blossom - Best hand trap in the game IMO. We are a going 2nd deck, so we want to be sure to load up on hand traps to disrupt our opponent from setting up an unbreakable board. She also gives access to Purgatrio. Nemeses Keystone - An aptly named card, this is a key component in a lot of the plays our deck can make. Gives good value when fused off of Fossil Fusion or Invocation from the GY, helping to keep our hand stocked for Mechaba and Skull King. Not only that, but he's an easy access special summon to set up easy link summons (I'm looking at your, Cross-Sheep) and can recycle our fusions back into our extra deck. Magical Meltdown - Tutors Aleister. Dark Hole - I was running Lightning Storm, but the fact that we have Magical Meltdown in play a lot of the time made it a pretty big nonbo for the deck. We only get to play 1 Raigeki, so Dark Hole helps us get tasty fusion targets in our opponent's yard to set up our big plays. Extra-Foolish Burial - The ultimate swiss army knife of the deck. It gets you missing combo pieces for fusion, or it can bin any of your fossils that work out of the GY. It has so many situations it's useful in that it's hard to list them all. Fossil Fusion - Makes our Fossils. Harpie's Feather Duster - This was another card that was Lightning Storm, but again that card was too much of a problem with Magical Meltdown. I wanted a main-deck out to Mystic Mine, and this is the best S/T removal in the game. Invocation - Just 1 copy since Aleister can find it easily, and we have access to effectively 7 copies of him in the deck between him, Meltdown, and Terraforming. Miracle Rupture - Sets up our GY as well as acts as a tutor when paired with Weathering Soldier. Don't leave home without 3. Raigeki - The freshmaker. Easy, low-risk board removal. Raigeki is as Raigeki does. Terraforming - Effectively copy #4 of Magical Meltdown, as we don't run any other field spells. Naturally if you wanted to side any field spells, this would act as a nice redundancy piece for them as well. Time Stream - 3 may seem like a lot, but you really want to start with 1 in hand for the lines where you want it. If you can't easily make a big Fossil monster, you can make a Skull Bone, Time Stream it, remove if from GY to tutor another Time Stream, and then Time Stream the Skull Knight into either Skull King or Skullgios. Impertinence - 2nd best hand trap in the game, and gives us some traps on the off chance we want them for Mechaba. Extra deck: Mechaba - Best Invoked monster. Easy access to it by normal summoning Aleister and linking him into Almiraj and then Secure Gardna. Skullgios - Often the strongest Fossil Fusion. Not much to say here. Skullgios ends games. Magellanica - We have a lot of Earth monsters, so this is an easy include. Nice and big to help us OTK. Conveniently also a Rock monster for Fossil Fusion. Skull King - This is the fossil we most often will fuse in to, so we play 2. He's easier to access than Skullgios, and can often be better. He's also our strongest fossil monster to lead off with if we are forced to go first. Augoeides - We make a lot of fusions, so this is a no brainer. Very often the best way to kill if our initial wave of fusions get answered. Purgatrio - Ash Blossom and Almiraj give us access to this. Great on a lot of boards. Skull Knight - Often just the in-between for Skull King or Skullgios. His remove from GY effect can also be relevant. Skullgar - Less useful than his cousin Skull Bone, but sometimes exactly what you need. Notably the highest attack Cross-Sheep target in the deck. Skull Bone - Sets up an easy Skull King or Skullgios with the aforementioned line using Time Stream. Knightmare Phoenix - Having an MST in the extra deck is too useful. I never leave home without 1. Secure Gardna - Almost strictly a Mechaba enabler, but he can sometimes clutch out a game by turning a simple Keystone -> Linkuriboh into 1000 attack. Cross-Sheep - Always be on the look out for lines involving this little guy! He easily can turn what would be a turn shy 8000 damage into an OTK. Too many ways to enable him in the deck to list, so just be looking for it. Linkuriboh - We have easy to play 1 star monsters, so we play Linkuriboh. Sometimes it's also nice to be able to force a Keystone into the GY to set up a fossil fusion. Almiraj - Only needed for the Secure Gardna -> Mechaba line, which is extremely important.

deck_excerpt: Hand loop for 5 every time
deck_description:
This is a digustingly consistent deck, there are basically 2 combos that you can pull off pretty much every time as long as you don´t draw either the coltwing or the candoll: For the first one, you start just with deskbot 003
  1. normal 003, summon 001
  2. summon halqifibrax, summon 001
  3. summon auroradon, summon 3 tokens, trigger and summon both 001s
  4. synchro the 001s with two tokens for 2 arc lights
  5. overlay arc lights into gallant granite, detach 1 to search ophiel, arc light triggers search chalislime
  6. use auroradon´s effect to tribute 1 token and granite to summon coltwing, trigger coltwing summon 2 tokens, trigger arc light search aquamirror, trigger both 001 s and summon
  7. use 001s and tokens for arc light and quandax
  8. overlay coltwing and arc light for dugares
  9. activate chalislime to discard a card, summon candoll, trigger candoll search inception
  10. use inception to summon ophiel by tributing candoll, trigger ophiel search phul
  11. use inception´s graveyard effect, discard chalislime, summon talismandra and add inception to hand, talismandra trigger search gustkraken
  12. use inception to summon gustkraken by tributing talismandra, trigger gustkraken see 2 cards of the opponents hand shuffle 1 into the deck [1]
  13. use dugares second effect, detach 2 materials and summon 1 arc light (not the one you detach) from grave, trigger arc light search another gustkraken
  14. use aquamirror to summon gustkraken by tributing the gustkraken on the field, trigger gustkraken [2]
  15. use aquamirror graveyard effect, shuffle it back in the deck and add gustkraken to hand from grave
  16. synchro quandax and arc light into omega, trigger arc light search aquamirror
  17. use omega´s effect, banish a card from the opponents hand [3]
  18. use aquamirror to summon gustkraken with gustkraken, trigger gustkraken [4]
  19. aquamirror effect in grave, shuffle back and add gustkraken back
  20. Use Ophiel effect to ritual summon gustkraken with Ophiel and Phul, trigger Gustkrakes [5]
For the second one, you need 1 Impcantation chalislime and 1 Megalith Ophiel, both of which are searchable by senju, manju and preparation of rites
  1. Normal senju/manju, add whichever piece you are missing
  2. Activate chalislime, discard a card and summon candoll, search inception with candoll
  3. use inception, summon ophiel with candoll, trigger ophiel search phul
  4. inception grave effect, discard chalislime, add to hand and summon talismandra, trigger talismandra add gustkraken
  5. Use inception, summon gustkraken with talismandra, trigger gustkraken [1]
  6. use Ophiel effect, summon phul with ophiel, trigger phul add ophiel back to hand
  7. use phul effect, summon hagith from the deck with ophiel, trigger hagith search unformed
  8. overlay 2 level 4s into granite
  9. use granite search researcher
  10. special summon researcher
  11. use granite and the other level 4 to summon cross-sheep
  12. use cross-sheep to summon linkross, trigger linkross summon 2 tokens
  13. use researcher and 1 token for metal marcher, trigger metal marcher summon back researcher
  14. use researcher and gustkrakes for omega
  15. use omega effect [2]
  16. use metal marcher and token for arc light
  17. use arc light and linkross for halqifibrax, trigger halqifibrax and arc light, summon 001 and search aquamirror
  18. use 001 and halqifibrax for auroradon, trigger auroradon summon 3 tokens, trigger 001 and summon
  19. use 001 and 1 token for arc light
  20. auroradon effect, tribute 2 tokens for coltwing, trigger coltwing summon 2 tokens, trigger 001 and summon
  21. use 001 and a token for arc light
  22. overlay both arc lights for dugares
  23. use dugares effect, detch 2 summon first arc light (NOT THE ONES DETACHED), trigger both arc lights, search gustkraken and benten
  24. use aquamirror to summon gustkraken with benten, trigger gustkraken and benten, shuffle and search senju/manju [3]
  25. use aquamirror effect, shuffle back and add gustkraken back
  26. use dugares and arc light for n´tss, trigger arc light search aquamirror
  27. use aquamirror to summon gustkraken with gustkraken, trigger gustkraken [4]
  28. use aquamirror effect, shuffle back and add gustkraken back
  29. use unformed to summon hagith from the deck by tributing the senju/manju and the n´tss (or another lever 4 you might happen to have), trigger hagith search another unformed (optional)
  30. Use hagith effect, summon gustkraken with hagith and the last token, trigger gustkraken [5]
Tere are ways to do the second combo without normal summoning the senju/manju first by burning your first unformed on anything and normal summing the senju/manju at the end, but those are better experimented in person.

deck_excerpt: An awesome Gimmick Puppet Deck that wipes your opponent's board during either player's turn.
deck_description: This deck is as competitive as I could make Gimmick Puppets (GP). The main goal is to get "GP Dreary Doll" into the GY asp. Until Maxx "C" comes back, going second sucks in this game and pure GP sucks to, so if this deck is to have a chance of being viable, it has to have as many board breaking cards as possible. The main combo is kaiju your opponent’s problem monsters, then SS “GP of Strings” or "Dingirsu" somehow, then upgrade it into #84, then clear the board with #84’s effect, then upgrade #84 into #77 for 4000 burst damage, then finish by upgrading #77 into "Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus - Sky Thunder" during MP2, which really throws a monkey wrench into your opponent's next turn. If you happen to have “Condolence Puppet" in your GY, you can banish it to protect Divine Arsenal from being destroyed card effects. If you’re lucky you can bust out two #77s with “Inferno Reckless Summon” for game. I recently discovered the "Zoo King Alpha" card and tried it out. Initially, it did well but I had to boot the "GP Gear Changers" to make room for them. I've had alot of success with it especially since GP have low ATK and the kaijus I give my opponent have high ATK. The bane of this deck is back row and negates, so save your Feather Duster and Lightning Storms until you're sure you can compromise your opponent with Divine Arsenal for the rest of the game. I also tried #97 and It works pretty well to, but only if your opponent literally has nothing to stop that 9000 attack, which they usually do.

deck_excerpt: Magistus Invoked
Consistent Marjoram Halqifibrax turbo basically
deck_description:
Edit Post Banlist December 2020: Well, a new banlist was dropped so I wanna update the list just a little bit so it fits with the upcoming format. Looks like another one had to die for the sins of our boy Halqifibrax, yay :D and so, there wasn't any hit to the deck, the only change I've made was just replacing 3 copies of Droll in the side deck for 3 copies of Lancea since Dragon Link should be no longer a problem compare to the upcoming top tier decks. This deck is for those who want to try out not the fun casual way these plant waifus was designed for but the more competitive way as a rogue deck for... maybe a chance to somewhat compete against metas. If you've never played Aromage before, I recommend trying the pure & casual version first so you can have a better look at the idea of how this plant archetype works. Also, just a quick reminder that this is a combo deck so you'll be seeing the same combo over & over again.

Strategy & Main Combo:

This deck focuses around 1 main combo which will end on a board with Crystron Halqifibrax + Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram + Blessed Winds... and maybe a Rose Girl added back to the hand as a bonus, why not? You can simply use Blessed Winds to gain LP and pop with Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram. Crystron Halqifibrax can be used to accel synchro summon with Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram during your opponent's turn: Formula Synchron into Borreload Savage Dragon for negate or Shooting Riser Dragon into either Satellite Warrior for a double pop or Crystron Phoenix to deal with a heavy backrow. Also, it is so easy to OTK with this deck thanks to the swarming ability of plant monsters and all the good synchro beatsticks got enough atk for an easy Borrelsword Dragon OTK. The main way to open your combo is to bring out 2 plants to make Aromaseraphy Jasmine and another monster for the tribute of it's effect. There're multiple ways & cards combinations in this deck that can accomplish this:
  • Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio + 1 monster: Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio send 1 monster from the hand to the GY → ss Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra → add Instant Fusion → ss Aromaseraphy Jasmine & Thousand-eyes Restrict. If you also have a LP gainer like Aroma Gardening you can use it to trigger Aromaseraphy Jasmine's effect & get a search.
  • Evil Thorn + Aromage Laurel: Evil Thorn burn for 300 & ss 2 other copies → ss Aromage Laurel → ss Aromaseraphy Jasmine using Aromage Laurel & 1 copy of Evil Thorn → gain LP & get a search.
  • Evil Thorn + LP gainer: Evil Thorn burn for 300 & ss 2 other copies → ss Aromaseraphy Jasmine & use LP gainer → search Aromage Laurel & ss it.
  • Evil Thorn + Super Solar Nutrient: Evil Thorn burn for 300 & ss 2 other copies → Super Solar Nutrient 1 Evil Thorn into Aromage Laurel → ss Aromaseraphy Jasmine & gain LP → search another Aromage Laurel & ss it.
  • Aromage Jasmine + LP gainer: If you happen to not open with any of the previous combos, you may have to try your luck on that Aromage Jasmine's draw and hope for another extender. However, If you've already opened with one, this is a good way to start off your combos for that extra plus.
There're still many ways to open the combo depending on your opening hand that I can't list all of them here but you'll eventually find the way playing the deck. Now to the main combo: Aromaseraphy Jasmine tribute 1 monster to ss Lonefire Blossom → Lonefire Blossom tribute Aromaseraphy Jasmine to ss Spore → Spore link into Linkuriboh → ss Spore using it's effect → make Crystron Halqifibrax with Spore & Linkuriboh → Crystron Halqifibrax ss Rose Girl → make Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram with Rose Girl & Lonefire Blossom → search Blessed Winds → add back Rose Girl to the hand with it's effect.

Decklist & Ratios:

  • The main deck is 48 cards because there are lots of bricks for the combos so I increased both the amount of starters and staples to reduce the chance of drawing into multiple bricks.
  • This deck runs quite a lot of staples like handtraps compare to it's casual version because it usually takes you only 2-3 cards to get the combo going while there're not that many extenders available for plant archetypes and the only good ones I can think of are One for One & Monster Reborn.
  • The Called by the Grave hit definitely hurted the deck since it's a rogue combo deck, thankfully Psy-framegear Gamma still gives the deck some help protecting Lonefire Blossom, Super Solar Nutrient, Evil Thorn & One for One from getting handtrap. However, I personally don't like running Triple Tactics Talent as a replacement for Called by the Grave because, as I mentioned, the deck doesn't have that many good extenders to draw into after getting handtrap.
  • 2 copies of Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra instead of 1 because the Predaplant combo is quite important due to how much consistency it gives the deck. You'll still have about 10% chance of drawing into it if playing only at 1 copy in a 48 cards deck, but approximately 1% chance of drawing all copies of it if playing at 2 (Yes, I unironically did the math on yugioh.party).
  • There are multiple lv3 to send with Shooting Riser Dragon for making Satellite Warrior, but the only lv4 for making Crystron Phoenix I play is World Carrotweight Champion. It's a plant with good stats so in case of drawing it, you can try to send it to the GY and shuffle it back with Blessed Winds if needed for the effect of Shooting Riser Dragon. It also has a useful effect for spamming the field that works really well with Rose Girl since you can send Rose Girl to ss it then add Rose Girl back every turn. Otherwise there're not many lv4 I want to run in this deck.
  • Casual Aromage builds usually run more LP gainers but in this build I only run 5 since my strategy doesn't rely that much on them thanks to the Predaplant engine and I don't like drawing too many of them. Aromages don't have a good way to protect their backrows so relying too much on them would be a big weakness in this format which spell/trap removals are very commonly seen. Also, I only run the ones that let me decide when to gain LP so my Aromages ain't triggered accidentally.
  • 3x Aroma Gardening because it's the best one for my strategy I believe. It can be used in either player's turn, works really well with Blessed Winds's revival effect and has an extra defensive effect. Although it's only once per turn so drawing too many copies might be a bad thing but I think it's worth to increase the chance of having it.
  • Aroma Garden is more important in casual builds since the atk/def boost definitely helps a lot to prevent Aromaseraphy Jasmine from being destroyed... but not that much in this build which doesn't end with Aromaseraphy Jasmine so I only run 1.
  • 2x Blessed Winds so if the first one get blowed away (which happens a lot when I try playing against metas), I can try to make a 2nd Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram to search the other one since Blessed Winds helps out a lot during grind games. You can also run the other Aroma traps (Humid Winds & Dried Winds), I just don't like playing too many backrows.
  • 2 spell/trap removals because this deck still struggles against backrows when going 2nd, especially floodgates.
  • 2 targets for Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra to search so it's easier to go +1 and Super Polymerization is a very good one in this format.
  • It's really up to you to choose Instant Fusion's target, I personally like Thousand-eyes Restrict as a good way to deal with monsters that cannot be destroyed and it helps opening for an OTK too. You can also use Mudragon of the Swamp as a 2nd Super Polymerization's target or Sea Monster of Theseus as a good lv5 tuner,...
  • You must have noticed that Predaplant Verte Anaconda but without the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon engine, the deck can definitely run it well like most other rogue decks if you'd like to. It's just me, I've already run 48 cards to avoid bricks and I don't like any extra bricks. I run Super Polymerization though and it works really well with Predaplant Verte Anaconda too thanks to it's effect. It's also a good way to link non-plant monsters into a plant one to make Aromaseraphy Jasmine or to be sent to the GY with Blessed Winds as a way to play around Mystic Mine.

Side Deck & Tech Options:

Giving the opponent LP advantage would be a big risk in this deck as it could potentially prevent Aromage Jasmine, Aromage Laurel & Aromaseraphy Angelica's effects which are very important. That's why I'll be avoiding cards like Cosmic Cyclone, Red Reboot, Solemn Judgment,... despite how good they are. Here are what I'm currently using:
  • 1x Dinowrestler Pankratops: good for going 2nd, can definitely help for a Borrelsword Dragon OTK.
  • 3x Nibiru, the Primal Being: good against most combo decks. If used successfully, it can help setting up an easy Borrelsword Dragon OTK so make sure to think about summoning the token in atk position if you see the opportunity. It can also be tributed for Aromaseraphy Jasmine's effect if necessary.
  • 3x Artifact Lancea: good against a lot of current top tiers like Virtual World, Dino, Invoked, Eldlich,... and may stop stuffs like Evenly Matched.
  • 3x Forbidden Droplet: good against multiple negates and monsters that cant be targeted like Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax,... which the deck definitely struggles to deal with. Running Dark Ruler No More may not be a good idea in this deck as you won't be able to use Evil Thorn's effect afterward.
  • 2x Lightning Storm: good against backrows.
  • 3x Evenly Matched: also good against backrows, the main deck is 48 cards so it's harder to get access to backrow removals than usual. It can deal with Secret Village of the Spellcasters or some other heavily set up boards too.
Side cards are totally optional and there're still a lot other good options in this format that can definitely work well with this deck you can try out like Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju,... Also, there're not many floodgates I could think of that would work well with this deck. YES, the deck can definitely run Mystic Mine pretty well not only to annoy other rogue players who thought their decks could even be able to play competitively, just like you, but also to insanely increase the level of interaction of this game, which is great. You know what, let's freaking pump up even more copies of Cauldron of the Old Man to furthermore increase the suffering. Why even try playing around Mystic Mine when you can just play it in the first place, am I right?

Some Notes & Tips:

  • If you're using Artifact Lancea, just keep in mind that it could also prevent Crystron Halqifibrax & Crystron Phoenix from using their effects during your opponent's turn so use it carefully.
  • If you're using Crystron Halqifibrax for Formula Synchron you may want to try not to chain it to something else so the draw effect doesn't miss timing.
  • You can only accel synchro summon during the main phase so if your opponent tries to go to the battle phase for an Evenly Matched make sure to get your Borreload Savage Dragon at the end of their main phase 1. It's also best to use Crystron Phoenix at the end of main phase after your opponent has finished setting up their backrows.
  • Successfully Psy-Framegear Gamma a handtrap while doing your combo and you can make Borreload Savage Dragon after Aromaseraphy Jasmine is tributed for an extra negate.
  • You can use Blessed Winds to shuffle Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra back if you need to re-use the Predaplant engine.
  • Only banish plant monsters that won't have potential uses with Spore since there won't likely be a way to bring them back so be sure to avoid Aromage monsters, Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra,...
  • Cauldron of the Old Man doesn't require an Aromage monster to be used so Aromage Laurel can then be ss to link with another random plant monster into Aromaseraphy Jasmine, gain LP & search Aromaseraphy Angelica to go full combo.
  • Try to have another way of gaining LP during your opponent's turn like Aroma Gardening or search Aromaseraphy Angelica with Aromaseraphy Jasmine so you can save Blessed Winds for the revival effect.
  • Try to have both Aromage Laurel & Linkuriboh in the GY so that instead of simply using Blessed Winds's 2nd effect to gain LP, you can use the revival effect to bring back Aromage Laurel and tribute it with Linkuriboh's quick effect. That way you'll both gain LP to trigger Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram to pop and get an extra battle protection. This is also a good thing to do when Blessed Winds get blowed away as you can still decide when to pop with Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram.
  • Put Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram in def position to avoid Lightning Storm, Crystron Halqifibrax can tag out for a synchro tuner in def position too so your opponent will likely have to choose your backrows.
  • If Shooting Riser Dragon's level change effect got handtrap, you can still use the Aromage Laurel summoned back with Blessed Winds to make Borreload Savage Dragon, then gain LP & pop with Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram.
  • If you open with Rose Girl and have to use 1 of her effects in order to do the combo, it's ok since Crystron Halqifibrax can also ss Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring as a lv3 tuner instead.
  • If you open with Spore, you'll have to try to send it to the GY with cards like Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio or Super Solar Nutrient then ss any lv1 like Aromage Laurel or Aromaseraphy Angelica when tributing Aromaseraphy Jasmine with Lonefire Blossom's effect to make Linkuriboh for the standard combo. If you still can't get access to Spore's effect however, you may have to ss Rose Girl when tributing Aromaseraphy Jasmine with Lonefire Blossom to make Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram and end without Crystron Halqifibrax.
  • If you get Mystic Mined after setting up your standard board... there's not much you can do to prevent Mystic Mine from resolving beside Twin Twisters sadly. But there's still this thing you can do to get rid of it, just link Crystron Halqifibrax & Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram into Predaplant Verte Anaconda and send it to the GY during your opponent's next end phase with Blessed Winds so you don't have any monster left. Then you can try to play Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram beatdown so you can send her to the GY anytime with Blessed Winds in case they got another Mystic Mine. Also, Predaplant Verte Anaconda can be shuffled back with Blessed Winds too if you need to get rid of non-plants. If they also got Field Barrier however, you may need backrow removals for that. Also, that Cauldron of the Old Man may comes in handy for these situations if you know what I mean.
  • This is obvious but, you can change 1 of your opponent's monster into a dark with Predaplant Verte Anaconda to use Super Polymerization even if they don't have any dark. It's just another way to deal with monsters that cannot be destroyed.
  • This deck doesn't do that good as it looks during grind game against heavy control decks, so try to go for a quick Borrelsword Dragon OTK if you can (at least that's how I stole most the games against metas).
There're also a couple ways to bait or play through a certain handtraps (even Nibiru) I've found but they're very situational & depended on opening hand so you'll have to find out for yourself. I think that's been a bit too much it feels like I'm teaching you how to play the game or something so I'm just gonna end it up here. This is my most favorite deck and I hope you'll also enjoy it like I do. Credit to T__J_91 - a random youtube channel I've found - for the idea! You can check out his/her channel for more Aroma builds.

deck_excerpt: Turbo out the unfair S0: Utopic Future Zexal with and back it up with material replenishment and s/t protection from the Time Thieves. Or deal huge da
deck_description: Hello everyone, this my first deck profile I'm submitting so please pardon me if I do something wrong. The point of this Numeron deck is like most, turbo out Utopic Zexal or Megaclops with ease, but the Time Thieves provide some useful support. Time Thief Redoer can banish itself from the field allowing Numeron Calling to activate, and thanks to Time Thief Winder we can easily search Retrograde, which is an counter trap that can negate an S/T and attach it to a Time Thief xyz. This is particularly useful against the common Infinite Impermanance, which would render our S0 useless. The ideal first turn is to summon Redoer with Regulator bringing out Winder and Bezel Ship, search Retrograde with Winder, banish Redoer by its own effect, and then activating Calling either by Network or in your hand to summon 3 Gates and make S0. When Redoer returns in the end phase your Retrograde will be live. On following turns you can summon Perpetua and attach Time Thief cards from the deck to S0 as xyz materials, keeping its attack up and allowing it to continue using its effect. If you want to push you for damage you can simply summon the 4 gates and attack with them, which can net easy otks in simplified gamestates. Megaclops is a backup "Towers" that can also be bought out with the Gates and can recur xyzs from the gy but not turn its summoned.     I won't pretend this a meta contender or the best use of the Numeron Engine, but I think it has some interesting synergy. I've been playing a lot of Time Thief variants so expect more of that in the future, especially with some of the fantastic cards in Phantom Rage and Genesis Impactors. Thank you for reading my ramblings.

deck_excerpt: And yet ANOTHER Charmer-based deck... This deck, specifically will be regularly updated as new lines of cards come out. This update will focus on the
deck_description:
You might already be able to tell, but I specialize in using the Charmers. I've been trying to make them as viable as possible without resorting to super cheep moves (like Dragun/Dragoon, for example), and while trying to keep the deck at least 60% Charmer/Familiar Possessed related. This deck, specifically will be regularly updated as new lines of cards come out. This update will focus on the new Magistus Archetype. Highlighted Cards: Magistus Flame Zoroa                                                [★4]  [Spellcaster/Tuner/Effect] [ATK/1500 DEF/1500] ⌈Magistus Dragon Vafram⌋                                       [★8]  [Dragon/Synchro/Effect]  [ATK/2500 DEF/2900] ⌈Magistus Goddess Ninaruru⌋                                 [☆4]  [Rock/Xyz/Effect]                 [ATK/1800 DEF/2400] ⌈Magistus Maiden Artemis⌋                                      [§ 1]   [Spellcaster/Link/Effect]    [ATK/ 800] Other Additions: Awakening of the Possessed - Great Inari Fire [★5]  [Pyro/Effect]                            [ATK/2000 DEF/ 200] ⌈Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter⌋                         [§ 2]  [Spellcaster/Link/Effect]     [ATK/1300] Removed: Fairy Tail - Luna                                                            [★4]  [Spellcaster/Effect]                 [ATK/1850 DEF/1000] Blizzard Princess                                                          [★8]  [Spellcaster/Effect]                 [ATK/2800 DEF/2100] Endymion Lab                                                                [ ∞ ] Card Trader                                                                     [ ∞ ] ______________________________________________________________________________ To start, so far Magistus Flame Zoroa has proved a useful addition to the deck. One of the more tricky things to do in this deck was Summon a Level 8 Synchro monster. Since the only Tuner in the Deck was Angraecum Umbrella, and most of the other monsters in the deck were either Level 3 or 4, unless you had any of the Awakening Possessed monsters out, you could only summon Level 6, 7, or 9 monsters. Not that it was particularly necessary to do so in the first place... With that being said, Zoroa being a Level 4 Tuner means he's a perfect tool for summoning almost anything in your Extra Deck, no matter what other monster is out:
  • If he's out with a Lv 3 Charmer, you can bring out ⌈Fortune Lady Every⌋ or ⌈Arcanite Magician⌋ easily.
  • If he's out with a Lv 4, you can bring out ⌈Time Thief Redoer⌋, ⌈Magistus Goddess Ninaruru⌋, or ⌈Magistus Dragon Vafram⌋, easily.
  • If he's out with a Lv 5 Awakening Possessed monster, you can bring out ⌈Datascape Fox - Xianxian⌋ easily.
  • And of course he can easily bring out at least 1 of your Link Charmers with ANY monster out, since he is a FIRE monster.
Zoroa's effect is super versatile as well. First of all, it's a Spellcaster with 1500 DEF, which is perfect for this Deck and is why I put him in here in the first place. Since its effect is a "1 per turn" effect, you can keep using it until you run out of Extra Deck cards to use on it.  Also, with the new cards in the Extra Deck, you can use Zoroa's effect for a variety of situations. If you use his effect on ⌈Magistus Maiden Artemis⌋, you can bring out another Zoroa, so that if something happens to your Zoroa on the field, you can just Summon another one next turn. Or if you have Grand Spirit Art - Ichirin [F] on the field, you can then swap your other Zoroa for your Inari Fire, which can set you up for an easy Link, Xyz, or Synchro Summon. If you're in a pinch where you opponent has a powerful monster out, as long as it can be destroyed by card effects, you can use Zoroa's effect on ⌈Magistus Dragon Vafram⌋. Then, not only are you safe from most Spell/Trap effects, but you can destroy almost any opponent's monster, nearly risk free. ⌈Magistus Goddess Ninaruru's⌋ effect isn't nearly as versatile with Zoroa's effect as the other two, but if you're close to end-game and your opponent's field is weak, you can use it to clear the field, then let your powerful monster(s) attack. Now let's talk about the new Extra Deck monsters' stand-alone effects:
  • ⌈Magistus Dragon Vafram⌋ has a very self-explanatory stand-alone effect. It makes your opponent hesitant to attack it, for fear of a full, one-sided, field-nuke. If you already have Nefarious Archfiend of Nefariousness in your GY, you can troll your opponent's fear by just using Nefarious's GY effect. Since it destroys the monster you target, ⌈Vafram's⌋ will activate, anyway. That way you'll still have a versatile monster on the field, and you still get your field-nuke. Even better, if you already had Unpossessed [∞] out, since ⌈Vafram⌋ was destroyed, you could use said Trap to bring out Zoroa. Then on your next turn, just use Zoroa's effect to equip it with ⌈Magistus Goddess Ninaruru⌋. Now, along with ⌈Ninaruru's⌋ effect, you get 3 Direct 1500-point Attacks.
  • ⌈Magistus Goddess Ninaruru⌋ is slightly less useful. If you're out of Familiar-Possessed monsters when Awakening of the Possessed [∞] is still on the field, you can use ⌈Ninaruru's⌋ effect to bring one of them back. Then Summon it to get your Draw. If you already have Grand Spirit Art - Ichirin [F] on the field, you could use her effect to bring out one of your Charmers or other elemental Spellcasters, and swap it out with one of the Familiar monsters (Jigabyte, Inari Fire, Ranryu, Nefarious Archfiend of Nefariousness). You could also use her effect on one of the Dogmatika monsters. Then just Special Summon it with its effect. Heck, even use it on Zoroa, then you can just Summon him and use his effect to equip either ⌈Ninaruru⌋ or him with ⌈Vafram⌋. Then you can keep resurrecting Spellcasters without worrying about Spell/Trap effects, and you can bulwark your opponent's monsters with some slightly higher ATK.
  • ⌈Magistus Maiden Artemis⌋ is probably the least immediately useful monster when she is Summoned. In fact, it's likely best to avoid summoning her in most cases, and just use Zoroa's effect to equip her directly instead. There are a couple situations where her stand-alone effect would be useful. If your opponent already has an Extra Deck monster out, and you conveniently have both of your Dogmatika monsters and another Spellcaster in your hand, you could Summon all 3 (using Dogmatikas' effects to Special Summon them). Next, first Link Summon ⌈Artemis⌋ with the non-Dogmatika Spellcaster monster, then Xyz Summon ⌈Ninaruru⌋ with the Dogmatika monsters. Then ⌈Artemis's⌋ effect will activate and you can equip her to ⌈Ninaruru⌋, use her effect to bring out Zoroa, and use ⌈Ninaruru's⌋ stand-alone effect to bring back one of the Dogmatikas. Then just Special Summon that monster from your hand using its effect again. Even better, if you already had one of the Familiar monsters in your hand as well, you could then use their effects to Special Summon any of them, allowing you to Xyz Summon ⌈Time Thief Redoer⌋ as a final move before a double Xyz attack.
  • ⌈Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter⌋ is a little difficult to figure out, at the moment. If you know you'll be summoning a lot of monsters in one turn, I think this card could be useful. Especially if you plan on Synchro or Xyz Summoning or if your opponent has a powerful non-Xyz monster. It lets you change any Special Summoned monster's level to any number from 1 - 8. Then you can also destroy that monster and an opponent's monster with the same Level. So depending on how you want to use it, you can either Extra Summon a monster or destroy an opponent's monster. If you have Teamwork of the Possessed set at least 1 turn before you use ⌈Puzzlomino's⌋ effect, you could destroy up to 2 cards in succession. Use said Trap to summon a Charmer with a different Attribute than ⌈Puzzlomino⌋, destroy a card, and then change that monster's Level to your opponent's monster Level, and use ⌈Puzzlomino's⌋ other effect to destroy their monster. It works in and out of the Extra Zone, so you don't always have to sacrifice a Link monster to use the effect.
That's it for this deck. From here on, until there are any more support cards added, this will be my last Charmer Deck.

deck_excerpt: Ojama/Melffy deck for the September 2020 format
deck_description: THIS LIST CONTAINS CARDS THAT ARE CURRENTLY ONLY IN THE OCG.  The cutest deck ever made meets one of the ugliest archetypes ever printed. Since Melffy and Ojama monsters are both Level 2, Beast-Type, and share the same affinity for swarming the field it should come as no surprise that the two are perfect for each other. The main goal with this deck is to resolve Ojama Red or Rescue Cat as early as possible to begin building your board of Rank 2 Beast Xyz monsters or Link monsters, from there you can have a board with Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, Melffy Mommy with multiple materials, etc. Valerifawn can help to set up Ojama Red's effect for next turn by discarding Ojamgic for its cost, this will get you a Rank 2 Xyz (preferably Ronin Raccoon as it can not only survive for a long time will it has a Raccoon Token out, but that token can also later be used for more Link plays on your turn.)  As an additional option, instead of returning your Melffy monsters to the hand on your opponents turn, I have also included Wonder Xyz which will allow you to Xyz Summon on your opponents turn as well as being able to bait your opponent into using removal for it due to the threat of Playhouse (which is even more potent in this deck since Melffy Mommy will likely have +3 or 4 materials on her most any given time.)  As always, suggestions are welcome. :)

deck_name: Creed of Black Magic (2020 Post Sept Banlist)
deck_excerpt: Beat Double Iris into the ground!
deck_description: Basically, this deck was made in reaction to Double Iris Magician being unbanned. I went into this project with little expectations, but lo and behold: the deck functins in the Meta! It doesn't win a whole ton, but it's annoying and can work around blockades with surprising effeciency. It also took me two weeks to tweek and perfect (I'm a perfectionist, OK?), but as a whole I am completely satisfied with how it turned out.  The basic idea is to be flexable with it. What you really want to get out is Time Pendulumgraph with Timestar Magician, so that you can get rid of two cards your opponent controls (notice: with Time Pendulumgraph's wording, you can destroy something and then SEND A CARD TO THE GY WITHOUT TARGETTING IT. An effective way to get rid of Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon or, I dunno, Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon). This is an ideal, as it also allows you to summon Zarc real easy, so obviously it can be negated  by any Ash Blossom or Ghost Ogre even. Heck, Haunted Mansion can negate Timestar's protective effect.  But any way you look at it, Timestar is your ideal. Get him, and your Pendulum scale and Pendulum monsters are saved. You can also use his effect to add Chronograph Sorcerer, who is nessecary to summon Zarc. Can you tell I really didn't understand much of the support Magicians have if you use it right?  Speaking of a Pendulum scale, PENDULUM SUMMONING IS UNDERRATED. It really can save your butt. Not to mention that Called By the Grave doesn't really against this deck because the monsters don't go to the Graveyard, but that doesn't really matter because it's limitted now anyways...  but hey, it's kinda nice you can summon some of your most powerful monsters back from the dead every turn. Also about Pendulum summoning: you usually want Oafdragon and Black Fang in you Pendulum Zones. Oafdragon's recycling effect is invaluble, especially when you need another Harmonizing Magician to power your combos. Black Fang was chosen because... he's got a good effect when he's destroyed? Has multiples? Yeah, I really don't know. Harmonizing Magician or Double Iris will suffice.  Now, TO THE EXTRA DECK! Oh, gosh, I spent AGES on this. Zarc is an obvious Why not? card. Borreload Savage is there 'cause EPIC NEGATION. Also, he's probably the strongsst monster in the deck... yeah. Need him. Enlightenment Palladen is nice for recycling those spells you need (ie. Pendulum Call and Duelist Alliance). Clear Wing's an obvious choice with Nobledragon OR Metal Marcher (your pick), and Meteorburst Dragon's second effect is so darn useful today. Metal Marcher can be summoned by Halqifibrax, and can summon those Level 7s. Norito is a given since Oafdragon and Chronograph exist. Timestar I've already described. Abyss Dweller's there because... Abyss Dweller (also Graveyard effects need to be negated at some point). Avarmax is there as protection and as the second-strongest (if not strongest) card in the deck. He also is significantly easier to summon with Pendulum monsters :/ . Saryuja is just nice, since you can summon 3 dead monsters with 300 extra ATK. Metaltron is nice with this deck, as it recycles AND gets rid of your opponent's key cards on the field for a turn for relatively cheap (considering Pendulum monsters can be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck). Triple Burst is and easy-out spell negater that can do some damage and also can produce good fodder for Savage when you return Day-Breaker to your field using Triple's third effect. Day-Breaker's there for ease of access and destructive potential, also allowing 2 rebirths from the Extra Deck, giving him power. Halqifibrax is there because all decks with synchro additions are considered worthless without him (also he's there for Metal Marcher to be summoned, in turn letting Meteorburst or Clear Wing to be summoned with ease).  Now the main deck. This makes more sense when you have the Extra Deck laid out for you, so here it goes: Kaijus, Ash Blossom, Triple Tactic, Luna, and Effect Veiler are all self-explanatory (Effect Veiler instead of Impernance because this is a Spellcaster deck! Also, when paired with Oafdragon or Chronograph, it can make those level 7s). Oafdragon and Chronograph's uses have been listed before (recycling and Summon fuel respectively). Black Fang is a great recycler for Timestar when it's destroyed, also usful for any Extra Deck fodder you want (and I do mean ANY). White Wing is there for the summoning of Zarc and link fodder, but no other reasons. Doble Iris searches Time and Star Pendulumgraphs and has an epic pendulum effect (hence the reason she was banned: use pendulum effect, search Pendulumgraph card). Also nessecary for Zarc (no Odd-eyes here!). Harmonizing Magician is a BEAST, openning up all of your key plays (Timestar especially, though. It gets around the "banished when leaves the field" part) and being generally awesome. Can also be recycled by Oafdragon's pendulum effect, so she's not useless in the Extra Deck. Nobledragon, because now you can't draw out of cards (also gets pretty epic synchros out)! She's pretty uefull for when Halqifibrax is summoned too. Left and Right Hands are in for negation, though they are decent discard fodder for Pendulum Call. Star and Time Pendulumgraphs are just plain amazing (especially together) and are relatively easy to search. Duelist Alliance searches Pendulum Call, the Pendulumgraphs AND Double Iris (she counts as a "Pendulum Dragon" card). It's a nessecity, because Pendulum Call is amazing, allowing you to search a Pendulim scale from your DECK, all for 1 discard. Not to mention the cards are protected until the end of the turn. It's pretty sweet.  Many of the Side Deck cards are self-explainatory. The only one that isn't (Timegazer) is there because of Chronograph Sorcerer's pendulum effect, should you ever need it.  You can mess with this deck idea all you want. In fact, you may want some Haunted Mansion's in your side deck, in case your facing a deck that uses the GY like an extra two arms. To make it cheaper (but still effective), you can swap Triple Tactic for pot cards (I'd go with Avarice od Aquisitiveness. Riches locks you out of your Extra Deck for the turn). You can also replace Savage with any number of level 8 Synchros (there's dozens of them). I've found that Norito doesn't really come out that often (and honestly his effect is already repeated b so many others in the deck), so you could switch him out if you want. I didn't, 'cause it's freak'n Norito, but what works for you works for me. I won't have to deal with it.  I'm looking at probably making a Fusion rendition of this deck in the future, along with an Insect deck, just because (wish me luck on that one!). I've made several other decks, but none are really noteworthy, so if you want to see them, look them up (I have a Tenyi deck and Super Quant deck, along with another, older Super Quant deck and a really old Magician and Odd-eyes deck that sucks). Hopefully I'll make more decks in the future (thiswas actually fun!), so look out for them if they do come out. Have fun dueling!

deck_excerpt: A Smoke Grenade route that doesn't require an extender? Sounds good to me.
deck_description: So, this version of the Rokket list came out of my desire to incorporate Smoke Grenade of the Thief into the combos, to hand loop people for 1 targeted card. However, I didn't like that the combo route I'd seen required an additional extender. Instead, by incorporating Draco Masters of the Tenyi, we can burn the Herald (OR and extender to save it) and thus also get the combo even if we whiff on an extender, which to me feels a lot more reliable. It ends on Buster Lock + Savage + Dragoon, and with an extender also ends on Herald of the Arc Light (plus 1 hand loop, by summoning Vylon Cube, and synchro summoning Herald).  I think Dragoon is the best boss monster in Rokkets right now. It lets a deck that already plays through interruptions play through yet another interruption, and it helps break boards and contribute to absolutely insane ending boards. However, the dark Warrior package eats up too much space - it'd be fine to incorporate just the Codebreakers, but the Phantom Knights cards are really disruptive to the functioning of the deck (even if 10 negate boards are fun), and I don't think there are many worthwhile targets for the codebreaker package in the hand loop build. I'll definitely be trying using codebreakers to make Unchained Abomination in the future.  Chaos Dragon Levianeer helps break boards, but also contributes to the hand disruption, since it can be searched with Brotaur. The deck doesn't loop as many cards out of hands as Infernoble will, but even a single targeted snipe is great for providing the information you'll need to lock down games.  Go through the combo in the order it is played out in the Extra Deck and you should figure it out. You have to be mindful of zones for Triple Arrow with Tenyi link 3 and the Guardragons under them, pretty standard for decks running the guardragons. The real thing that might trip you up is you have to either make Herald + Halqifibrax into Draco Masters of the Tenyi OR you can use an extender here to end on an extra negate.
